	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">GradualGames wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">embarking on attempting to port an old DOS game to the SNES (assuming I have the rights to do this)</div><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If you have the rights, perhaps you can ask the original author [what the intended aspect ratio was]</div><br /><div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Rights? What does that mean? Are you going to get fined or sent to jail if you don't have the &quot;rights&quot; when you ask an author a question?</div><br />Asking the author a question isn't itself copyright infringement. But questions of authorial intent related to technical aspects of game graphics could signal to the author your intent to make an unauthorized port. This in turn could cause the author and/or publisher to perform a more thorough review of your other work for copyright violations. I ran into a similar issue back in March 1999.

		

		</td>
